ÔĽŅ{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":219640,"duration_api_ms":165636,"num_turns":26,"result":"I have all the evidence needed. Here is the full security audit of the auth implementation.\n\n---\n\n## Security Findings √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ internal-app Auth\n\n### 1. Hardcoded Default Password for All Employees\n\n**Files:**\n- `src/utils/orgManager.ts:794` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ employee accounts are provisioned with `hashPassword('12345')` when no password is supplied\n- `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:836` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ legacy employees (no stored hash) are authenticated by a plain-text equality check: `passwordValid = password === '12345'`\n\n**Vulnerability:** Every employee account created without an explicit password uses the literal string `\"12345\"`. Because `isLegacyEmployee` is true whenever `hashToVerify === ''` (which is the stripped state stored in `cachedUsers` after `setCachedUsers` zeroes the hash field), an attacker can log in as any employee account by just typing `12345`. The fallback is a plain-text comparison, not a scrypt verify call, so it can never be made constant-time regardless of future fixes elsewhere.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Auth Completely Bypassed When Electron API Is Unavailable\n\n**File:** `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:841`\n\n```ts\n} else {\n  passwordValid = true; // Browser dev mode fallback\n}\n```\n\n**Vulnerability:** If `window.electronAPI?.verifyPassword` is falsy (Electron API not yet initialised, preload script crash, sandbox mode, or any renderer-side error), the `else` branch executes and `passwordValid` is set to `true` unconditionally. Any user can authenticate as any account with any password string. This is a \"fail open\" pattern in a security-critical path.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Recovery Code Expiry Is Never Checked at Login\n\n**Files:**\n- `src/utils/auth.ts:119` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ `RECOVERY_CODE_EXPIRY_MINUTES: 10` defined; `generateRecoveryCode()` sets `expiresAt` to 10 minutes from now\n- `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:851` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ login validation is: `if (!rc.used && rc.codeHash === inputHash)`\n\n**Vulnerability:** The `expiresAt` field on `RecoveryCode` is set but never read during login. A recovery code issued once is valid forever until it is marked `used`. An attacker who observes a generated code (e.g., via shoulder-surfing, log leakage, or clipboard history) can use it days or months later.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Recovery Codes Hashed With SHA-256, Not scrypt\n\n**Files:**\n- `src/utils/auth.ts:111` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ browser fallback: `crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', enc.encode(code))`\n- `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:847` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ login-time: same `crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', enc.encode(password))`\n\n**Vulnerability:** Passwords use scrypt (N=16384, r=8, p=1). Recovery codes use raw SHA-256. A 10-digit decimal code has 10^10 possible values (~33 bits). SHA-256 can be computed at ~10 billion hashes/second on a consumer GPU. The entire recovery code space can be exhausted in under 1 second. If the `codeHash` values are ever exposed (GitHub vault breach, safeStorage compromise, or the `cachedUsers` state that gets persisted), every user's recovery code is instantly crackable.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Brute-Force Counter Lives Only in Memory √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ Resets on Restart\n\n**File:** `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:1098√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú1130` (the `partialize` callback)\n\nThe persisted state includes `cachedUsers`, `cachedStores`, `installMode`, etc., but **`loginAttempts` is absent**. On every Electron restart the counter resets to `{}`. An attacker gets 5 free attempts per process launch, giving unlimited effective tries against the 5-attempt lockout. On a 4-digit or `12345` default password this is trivially exploitable.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `ProtectedRoute` Grants Unconditional Access When `cachedUsers` Is Empty\n\n**File:** `src/components/ProtectedRoute.tsx:89√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú90`\n\n```ts\nif (!multiStoreEnabled && cachedUsers.length === 0) {\n  return <>{children}</>;\n}\n```\n\n**Vulnerability:** Any route decorated with `<ProtectedRoute>` is bypassed entirely if `cachedUsers` is empty. `cachedUsers` comes from Zustand persisted state, which is stored in the `bags-auth-storage` key in localStorage (the safeStorage fallback also uses this key name). If an attacker can clear that key √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ via XSS, a malicious Electron IPC handler, or direct filesystem access to the safeStorage file √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ all RBAC is disabled and every page is accessible without authentication.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `logout()` Does Not Revoke the Token √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ `isAuthenticated` Stays `true`\n\n**File:** `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:480√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú503`\n\n```ts\nlogout: async () => {\n  // DO NOT call clearToken() √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ PAT is permanent!\n  set({\n    multiStoreEnabled: false,\n    authMode: 'none',\n    ...\n  });\n  // isAuthenticated stays TRUE √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ PAT is still valid\n  // token stays in memory √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ for background sync\n```\n\n**Vulnerability:** After `logout()`, the GitHub PAT remains in `token`, `isAuthenticated` is `true`, and `user` retains the GitHub profile. Any renderer-side code that reads `useAuthStore.getState()` post-logout has a live, valid PAT. If the session is taken over (e.g., dev-tools, a malicious native module, or an IPC exploit), the attacker inherits a permanently valid GitHub token with no revocation path short of manually revoking it in GitHub settings.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Setup Token Embeds a Live GitHub PAT in Plaintext\n\n**File:** `src/pages/LoginPage.tsx` √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ `SetupGuide` component (the token builder section ~line 278+)\n\nThe setup token format is:\n```\nORION-<owner/repo>-<ghp_...>-<encryptionKey>\n```\n\nThe in-app token builder assembles this string from user-typed inputs and writes it to the clipboard. Anyone who intercepts this token string √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ via email, Slack, a screenshot, clipboard history, or log file √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ has a working GitHub PAT. The PAT is not scoped or rotated when the token is generated; it has the same lifetime and permissions as the original PAT the tech user created in GitHub settings.\n\n---\n\n### 9. Modulo Bias in Recovery Code Generation\n\n**File:** `src/utils/auth.ts:107√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú108`\n\n```ts\nconst digits = Array.from(crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(10)))\n  .map(b => (b % 10).toString()).join('');\n```\n\n**Vulnerability:** `b % 10` on a uniform byte (0√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú255) is not uniform over 0√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú9 because 256 is not divisible by 10. Digits 0√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú5 appear with probability 26/256 and digits 6√Ę‚ā¨‚Äú9 with 25/256. The bias is small (~0.4%) but it is a textbook cryptographic weakness. Combined with issue #4 (SHA-256 hashing), a cracker can prioritise lower digits and reduce the search space.\n\n---\n\n### 10. GitHub PAT Written to `localStorage` When Electron API Is Absent\n\n**File:** `src/store/useAuthStore.ts:1100`\n\n```ts\n...(!window.electronAPI?.encryptToken ? { token: state.token } : {}),\n```\n\n**Vulnerability:** If `electronAPI.encryptToken` is not defined √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ including during any startup window before the preload script registers it √Ę‚ā¨‚ÄĚ the raw GitHub PAT is serialised into the Zustand persistence blob and written to `localStorage`. `localStorage` in Electron's renderer is readable by any JavaScript in the same origin, meaning a renderer-side XSS or a malicious `require()`'d module that reaches the renderer can exfiltrate the token. The check is evaluated at persist time, so a race condition at startup can cause the token to be written even in production.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"4ce9a1e3-c8b3-4940-a254-a7528364dd68","total_cost_usd":0.48975854999999996,"usage":{"input_tokens":15,"cache_creation_input_tokens":69703,"cache_read_input_tokens":335691,"output_tokens":8508,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":69703,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":3491,"cache_read_input_tokens":81612,"cache_crea